<DOC><DOCNO> ZF32-101-220 </DOCNO><DOCID>11 179 225</DOCID><JOURNAL>Computer Weekly  July 25 1991 n1272 p6(1).andM;</JOURNAL><TITLE>US Air Force grounds C++. (commits to Ada programming language)</TITLE><AUTHOR>Flood, Gary.andM;</AUTHOR><TEXT><ABSTRACT>The US Air Force commits to use of the Ada programming languageinstead of the C++ object-oriented programming language after athree-month evaluation process.andP;  An Air Force report asserts thatthe maturity and tool support of the C++ language are three yearsbehind Ada and that C++ does not yet offer cost savings over Ada.andO;The report also showed that Ada scored significantly higher thanC++ in US Software Engineering Institute analyses for capability,maintainability, risk and in the overall evaluation.andP;  USconsultancy CTA found Ada productivity substantially higher thanC++.andP;  TRW evaluations concluded that Ada was 23 percent betterthan C++ for implementing management information systems and 24percent better for development of command and control system.andM;</ABSTRACT></TEXT><DESCRIPT>Product:   C++ (Program development software) (Military aspects).andO;Topic:     ADASoftware SelectionGovernment RegulationCriteriaReportsEvaluationComparisonUnited States. Air Force.andO;Feature:   illustrationphotograph.andM;</DESCRIPT></DOC>